    'date' => 'Mon, 11 Oct 1999 14:38:34 +1000',
    'body' => 'Some more real world data points on these topics :-

Human (most animal) vision is processed in the occipital cortex at the
back of the brain.
	The nerves from the retinae of each eye branch in such a way that the
half closer to the nose send fibres to the opposite hemisphere (so L ->
R and vice versa) while the lateral halves project to the same
hemisphere. The crossover is called the \'optic chiasm\'.
	In each hemisphere, the visual pathways travel through the geniculate
nuclei before reaching the cells of the occipital cortex.
	In the geniculate nuclei and visual cortex, the neurones that transmit
and process visual
data are organised into distinct \'dominance columns\'.
	The dominance column neurones were \'interrogated\' by the researchers to
reconstruct what the (anaesthetised) cats saw.
	Image reconstruction was based on a model of neuron network activity -
the electrical data obtained from the cats was plugged into the computer
and... you know the rest.

Re shooting and hemisphere dominance : the left cerebral hemisphere is
the dominant one in 85% of the population regardless of handedness.
	Eye dominance is a little harder to explain, but must have something to
do with training in early development - appropriate visual stimulation
must occur within the first 12-18 months of life if the geniculate
nuclei are to develop normally (as suggested by the experiments of Hubel
and Wiesel, et al. H. and W\'s. experiments were interesting in that by
applying various lenses or gratings over young cat\'s eyes, or by
colouring the environment appropriately, they could induce some profound
alterations in the development of the visual pathway).

Ob Travs :- the basis of synthetic vision (esp. pattern recognition for
robotics)(TTL 9-10), technological \'telepathy emulators\', part of memory
reading technology, neural activity sensor based surveillance (read
other\'s visual cortices/geniculates remotely), etc. etc.

Robert O\'Connor
Medico, Gamer
