You are *really* gonna hate yourself. There\'s a simple driver that
lets a PC access Atari ST disks. And it\'s been available for a *long*
time.

Just got back from a weeks holidays with the missus, so I\'m sorry for =
the delay in replying.

I am aware of emulators from the C64 onwards, but the problems I had at =
the time was the old floppies dying while replacements were not that =
easy to come by locally, and a desire to upgrade.  So the upgrade was =
the 1040ST for financial reasons, but locally, you could not find, let =
alone buy emulators and you couldn\'t get disk down-sizing anywhere if =
you could.  So eventually that stuff was sold, turfed, or given away.

Then the FDD in the ST died (I could never afford a HDD for the Atari, =
and right up until the Atari Australia folded, HDD\'s were still premium =
prices), so this stuff got stored before selling or giving away and =
then... I bought the PC.  So now, it was all moot for me, because I had =
to type in my work from hard copies whether I liked it or not.  When it =
came to the PC, the scanned images seemed to take up more of my HDD than =
Word documents did, so again, it was typing in from hard copies of the =
C64 and 1040ST to save space.

- -- The Roc

