<<snips discussion of why the 3I wouldn\'t use near-c rocks>>
> 
> Ok, now explain how come Lucan didn\'t use them in the Black War period
> of the Rebellion. He nuked quite a lot of planets bare, and
> intentionally left many other planets without the infrastructure to
> support their own populations, so near-c rocks would\'ve been right down
> his alley.

Note:  I am only discussing one madman\'s reluctance to use near-c rocks
routinely.  I take no sides in the debate of whether near-c rocks would
be a viable weapon under any other circumstances.

My main guess as to why Lucan didn\'t use near-c rocks as a routine
weapon:

It takes too long to bombard a world using near-c rocks.  Nukes, gas,
and germs are much quicker.  After all, to use near-c rocks, one must
first occupy the outer reaches of a star system, then fit some sort of
drive to rocks, then fire them, then wait for the rocks to hit.  With
nukes, one merely puts some bombardment ships in orbit, then suppresses
the defenses, then pops nukes as desired.  The same applies to gas and
germs.  Quick, easy, and deeply unpleasant for the target world\'s
inhabitants.

Lucan doesn\'t strike me as the type of tyrant who would be willing to
wait for results.

(BTW, if you haven\'t guessed by my language above, I always thought that
Lucan was the _least_ qualified contender for the Iridium Throne....)

